'''Florid cutaneous papillomatosis''' (also known as '''Schwartz-Burgess syndrome'''<ref name="eMedicine">{{EMedicine|article|1097463|Florid Cutaneous Papillomatosis}}</ref> and '''FCP'''<ref>{{cite book |author=Stedman |title=Stedman's Dermatology & Immunology Words: Includes Rheumatology, Allergy, and Transplantation |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |year=2001 |isbn=0-7817-3059-7 }}
</ref>) is the sudden onset of numerous cutaneous papillomas that are indistinguishable from viral warts, and associated with underlying malignancy.<ref name="eMedicine" /><ref name="Mansouri">{{cite journal |author=Mansouri, P., ''et al.'' |title=Florid cutaneous papillomatosis, malignant acanthosis nigrica, palmoplantar keratoderma, and gastric adenocarcinoma |journal=Acta Medical Iranica |volume=37 |issue=1 |year=1999 |url=http://journals.tums.ac.ir/upload_files/pdf/4884.pdf |format=PDF}}</ref>{{rp|63}}

== History ==
It was discovered by [[Robert A. Schwartz MD]] and [[Gordon H. Burgess MD]]. The original description was published in the ''Archives of Dermatology'',<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1001/archderm.114.12.1803 |author=Schwartz RA, Burgess GH |title=Florid cutaneous papillomatosis |journal=Arch Dermatol |volume=114 |issue=12 |pages=1803–6 |year=1978 |month=December |pmid=153731 |url=http://archderm.ama-assn.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=153731}}
</ref> which is published by [[American Medical Association]].

== Presentation ==
Florid cutaneous papillomatosis presents with verrucous papulonodules resembling viral warts.<ref name="eMedicine" /> These [[skin lesion]]s develop on the trunk, extremities, and face<ref name="Mansouri" />{{rp|63}}, and are almost twice as common in men than in women, especially individuals aged 53–72 years.<ref name="Mansouri" />{{rp|66}}  This papillomatosis may also present with other cutaneous signs of internal malignancy, such as [[acanthosis nigricans type I]] and [[Leser-Trélat sign|Leser-Trélat]].<ref name="Mansouri" />{{rp|66}}

== Etiology ==
Florid cutaneous papillomatosis is associated with underlying malignancy, most often [[gastric adenocarcinoma]]<ref name="Mansouri" />{{rp|63}}<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.4103/0378-6323.16238 |author=Singhi, M.K., ''et al.'' |title=Florid cutaneous papillomatosis with adenocarcinoma of stomach in a 35 year old male |journal=Indian J Dermatol Venereol Leprol |volume=71 |issue=3 |pages=195–6 |year=2005 |url=https://tspace.library.utoronto.ca/bitstream/1807/5515/1/dv05062.pdf |format=PDF |pmid=16394412}}</ref> but also with [[breast cancer]], [[bladder cancer]], [[hepatobiliary cancer]], [[ovarian cancer]], [[uterine cancer]],<ref>{{cite journal |author=Yoon Oo Noh, G.C.L., Mi Kyeong Kim, Youn Soo Kim, Tae Young Yoon |title=A Case of Florid Cutaneous Papillomatosis and Tripe Palm |journal=Korean J Dermatol |volume=7 |issue=40 |year=2002 |url=http://koreamed.org/SearchBasic.php?RID=291794&DT=1&QY=A+%5BALL%5D+Case+%5BALL%5D+Florid+%5BALL%5D+Cutaneous+%5BALL%5D+Papillomatosis+%5BALL%5D+Tripe+%5BALL%5D+Palm+%5BALL%5D}}</ref> [[prostate cancer]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}, and [[lung cancer]];<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1046/j.1468-3083.2000.00051.x |author=Bottoni U, Dianzani C, Pranteda G, ''et al.'' |title=Florid cutaneous and mucosal papillomatosis with acanthosis nigricans revealing a primary lung cancer |journal=J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=205–8 |year=2000 |month=May |pmid=11032067 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/resolve/openurl?genre=article&sid=nlm:pubmed&issn=0926-9959&date=2000&volume=14&issue=3&spage=205}}
</ref> however, the cause of FCP is currently not known.<ref name="eMedicine" />

